  "chunk_index": 27,
  "summary": "Inspector Spence and Hercule Poirot discuss the murder of Mrs. Upward at Golden Chain Manor, concluding that the killer was likely someone she knew. Evidence at the scene includes two coffee cups; although the guest's fingerprints were wiped away, lipstick traces remain on one rim. Spence notes that Mrs. Upward had recognized a photograph of Lily Gambol, which links this crime to the McQuitty murder case. It is believed that Mrs. Upward was playing detective and summoned a guest to her home while her son, Robin Upward, and Mrs. Oliver were at the theater. The maid, Frieda, was in her room and did not witness the event.\n\nDierdre Henderson arrives to provide a statement, claiming Mrs. Upward invited her for coffee between 8:30 and 9:00 PM. However, when Dierdre arrived, the house was dark and no one answered, leading her to assume Mrs. Upward had gone to the theater or out for a walk. Spence observes that Dierdre does not wear lipstick or perfume, which contrasts with the scent of expensive perfume reported by Mrs. Oliver and Robin Upward at the scene. \n\nSpence considers whether Dierdre could be Lily Garfield, though he notes their backgrounds differ, and he also contemplates Eve Carrington as a suspect due to her ability to afford expensive perfume. Finally, Spence confirms that a sugar hammer is the murder weapon, as it matches the wounds from the McQuitty case and contains traces of human blood.",
